section.amend:
WHEREAS, in accordance with Utah Code Section 49-20-201, the state participates in the Public Employees' Benefit Insurance Program (PEHP);WHEREAS, the state has authorized PEHP since 2011 to administer a pilot program for bariatric surgery for the state health insurance plan with an adjusted annual budget of $1,050,000;WHEREAS, a member must, among other things, meet medical criteria of over 40 BMI or over 35 BMI with certain comorbidities, participate in health coaching, and show an aptitude for weight loss over six months to qualify for the bariatric surgery pilot program;WHEREAS, data suggests that the class of drugs known as glucagon-like peptide-1 receptor agonists, known as GLP-1 drugs, could be an effective option for medically qualified members who may prefer a GLP-1 drug to bariatric surgery; andWHEREAS, the state desires to make available an alternative GLP-1 benefit for medically qualified members that would be limited in scope to stay within the adjusted budget of the bariatric surgery pilot program:NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the Legislature of the state of Utah, the Governor concurring therein, directs the Public Employees' Benefit Insurance Program, beginning with the 2026 plan year, to:(1) modify the current bariatric surgery pilot program to be the 'Weight Management and Obesity Pilot Program' and include an alternative GLP-1 treatment pathway;(2) define the parameters of the alternative GLP-1 treatment pathway for medically qualified members, including requirements that the program:
a. be administered on a reimbursement basis;
b. include 50% member cost sharing;
c. cap monthly PEHP allowed pharmacy expenses at $300 per member;
d. limit coverage to a 24-month period; and
e. align current bariatric surgery pilot program coaching and other participation requirements to also apply to the alternative GLP-1 treatment pathway;(3) permit medically qualified members who enter the Weight Management and Obesity Pilot Program to make a one-time choice between bariatric surgery and the alternative GLP-1 treatment pathway;(4) administer the Weight Management and Obesity Pilot Program to stay within the adjusted annual budget; and(5) before December 1, 2026, and each year thereafter until 2028, report to the Health and Human Services Interim Committee on the results of the Weight Management and Obesity Pilot Program.BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that a copy of this resolution be sent to the Public Employees' Benefit and Insurance Program.
